===Etymology===
First attested in this form around 1620 (referring to a {{l/en|bedbug}}), from earlier {{term|bugge||beetle|lang=en}}, a conflation of two words:
# {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|bugge||scarecrow, hobgoblin|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|bugja-|bugja-|swollen up, thick|lang=gem-pro}} (compare Norwegian {{term|bugge||big man|lang=no}}, dialectal Low German {{term|Bögge||goblin”, “snot|lang=nds}}
# {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|budde||beetle|lang=enm}}, from Old English {{term|budda|lang=ang}} (see {{term|scearnbudda||dung beetle|lang=ang}}), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|buddô|lang=gem-pro}}, {{recons|buzdô|lang=gem-pro}} (compare Low German {{term|Budde||louse, grub|lang=nds}}, Norwegian {{term|budda||newborn domestic animal|lang=no}}). More at {{l/en|bud}}.

